<br>
The air was thick with the scent of incense, which was ironically the thing Xarros was having the hardest time getting used to.  Apparently the teir'dal loved the various scents to the point of the air being barely breathable.  For a moment, he felt a pang of loss for Felwithe, and its clean and open air.  His entire existance as a dark elf had so far been confined to the dank caves of Neriak.<br>
<br>
That pang, was quickly followed by searing hate.  It was Tunare that left his soul for Innoruuk.  It was his &quot;mother&quot; that had cast him out for naught but a mistake, for a simple mortal error in believing that her avatar wasn't actually hers, but was a mockery of her.  She could have forgiven, she could have warned, she did neither.<br>
<br>
The hypocrisy of it, she was no better than Innoruuk in terms of her real disdain for the elves.  At least Innoruuk was honest about it.<br>
<br>
Ulraz S`Lon spat at him &quot;So you are the next pathetic maggot I have the displeasure of training to be a useful Shadowknight of the Lodge of the Dead. First you must get yourself outfitted in a suit of armor, those rags you wear can not even contain the stench of your miserable hide and will do no good protecting it from the edge of an enemies blade. &quot;<br>
<br>
Xarros nodded, then dared to speak, &quot;Where shall I find this armor?&quot;<br>
<br>
Ulraz S`Lon spoke &quot;Seek Krivn S'Tai in the Commoner quarter of Neriak and give him this request parchment. Krivn S'Tai has been paid in advance by the Lodge of the Dead for the requested service. Simply give him the request parchment and he will instruct you further.&quot;<br>
<br>
Ulraz continued quietly, so that only Xarros could here it, &quot;Do not make light of this chance...I argued that we should put your head on a pike for your origins, and I would gladly do so should you fail.&quot;<br>
<br>
Xarros paled under his blue skin, did they know his origins?<br>
<br>
&quot;No commoner such as yourself should have been allowed in here as a servant, let alone a knight in training.&quot; The venom in his voice was unmistakable.<br>
<br>
&quot;Rest assured, sir, that I will take every opportunity to make sure you *fully* appreciate my devotion to Innoruuk&quot; Xarros spoke back, his voice dry with sarcasm.  He had learned quickly, that wishing Innoruuk's blessings and appreciation upon others was both blessing and curse among the teir'dal.<br>
<br>
The distinction was not lost on Ulraz.  &quot;Perhaps you will, but you have much to prove before your words are anything other than just that.  Now begone filth, before your presence gives me excuse to indulge myself.&quot;<br>
<br>
With a curt bow, Xarros spun on his heels and left.  He stopped by the communal barracks he and the other squires shared, and retrieved his meager belonging.  Stepping outside of the Hall, he wandered down the long passageway that connected the cavern it was in to the rest of the Third Gate of Neriak.  <br>
<br>
Where he saw the ghouls that guarded the entry, and the festering corpse of some half elf, long since stripped of its gear and valuables.  He stopped and regarded the ghouls, who in turn seemed to regard him warmly, sensing the bond Innoruuk had placed on his soul, and securing his right to walk freely.<br>
<br>
&quot;I wonder if he was here for the same reason I was so long ago?&quot;  Xarros' experience in Neriak as a koad'dal priest was restricted to an assault into the edges of the Third Gate to secure a necessary component for another koada'dal, a paladin, to complete his quest for his holy sword.  He futily wished he had paid more attention to the maps of this place compiled from various spy reports. <p>--------------<br>
